  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The research conducted by Derek H. Janssens and colleagues explores how KMT2A oncoproteins contribute to epigenetic resistance against targeted therapies, highlighting significant implications for cancer treatment strategies. The study has been referenced in several prominent academic journals, indicating a notable level of influence within the field.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The preprint titled \"KMT2A oncoproteins induce epigenetic resistance to targeted therapies\" by Derek H. Janssens et al. offers crucial insights into the mechanisms by which KMT2A oncoproteins confer resistance in cancer therapies. Such findings are especially relevant given the rising challenges in effectively treating cancers that employ targeted therapies. This research was shared on bioRxiv, a platform known for facilitating the rapid dissemination of scientific knowledge, allowing for early engagement with the research community.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The work originates from several esteemed institutions, including Baylor College of Medicine and Fred Hutch Cancer Center, which underscores the collaborative effort and institutional investment in this area of cancer research. The diverse affiliations indicate a rich interdisciplinary approach that strengthens the study's credibility and potential impact across multiple facets of oncology.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">As indicated by its citations in reputable journals such as Cancers and Medical Oncology, this work has already begun to carve out a space in academic conversations surrounding cancer treatment. With six citations recorded in OpenAlex, it reflects an early uptake of the study's findings within the scientific community and suggests that the implications of the research are resonating with other scholars and practitioners.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Despite the lack of specific funding or widespread public discourse around this study, the proven downstream reuse of its materials signifies its role as a foundational contribution to ongoing research. In total, the proactive dissemination of this preprint reflects a commitment to open science, enhancing the conversation around KMT2A's role in therapeutic resistance and potentially informing future studies aimed at overcoming such challenges in cancer treatment.</p>",
